n and its consequences: Against the backdrop of the historical foundation of the turn to space at the beginning of the 21st Century, Stephan Günzel carves out the relevant lines of distortion the current debate shows, systematically declining the various aspects of spatialization by taking Henri Lefebvre's theory of the production of social space as an example. The delimitation of individual versions of the spatial turn distinctly shows the discipline-specific interests in space, making an interdisciplinary suggestion concerning its methodical examination based on topological structures possible. This book does not only provide a systematic overview of the spatial turn but also presents the theories about space by Ratzel, Simmel, Lewin, Heidegger, McLuhan, Levinas, Foucault, Spencer Brown, Bourdieu, Deleuze, de Certeau and others, which makes it particularly suitable for academic studies and teachings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGeographyxPhilosophy. 0aSpacexHistory. 0aSpacexSocial aspects. 4aBourdieu. 4aDe Certeau. 4aDeleuze. 4aEinführung. 4aFoucault. 4aHeidegger. 4aKultur. 4aKulturtheorie. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aLefebvre. 4aLevinas. 4aLewin. 4aMcLuhan. 4aMedien. 4aOrt. 4aRatzel. 4aRaumtheorie. 4aSimmel. 4aSpencer Brown. 4aTheorie der sozialen Hervorbringung. 4aTopologie. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aBourdieu.  aCultural Studies.  aCultural Theory.  aCulture.  aDeleuze.  aFoucault.  aHenri Lefebvre.  aIntroduction.  aLevinas.  aMedia.  aPlace.  aSpatial Theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2017z9783110548242oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978383943972240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839439722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839